{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01WKvsWgC2QxBEzZuw7SoP5p","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking me to create a test plan for an e-commerce product recommendation engine. I need to analyze each behavior and determine:\n\n1. The minimum test infrastructure level needed to catch real failures\n2. A description of the behavior\n3. A justification for the level choice\n4. A test description\n5. Whether the plan is consistent (test actually requires that level)\n6. Probability distribution across the 5 levels\n\nThe levels are:\n- **Unit**: one local function or object boundary, no I/O\n- **Integration**: several modules wired together, local DB or filesystem\n- **System**: subprocess, OS behavior, real HTTP, or real external API call\n- **Agentic**: result depends on real LLM non-determinism or a real model call\n- **Workflow**: multiple agentic steps in sequence, or a full agent pipeline\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n### Behavior 1: Products marked as out-of-stock are excluded\n- **Description**: Out-of-stock products should not appear in results regardless of score\n- **Mock-Miss**: Could a mock miss this? No, if we mock the inventory check, it's easy to verify the filter logic\n- **Real-Infra**: Does this depend on OS, network, real DB? Not necessarily - we could test this with an in-memory product database\n- **Mock-Hide**: Would mocking the inventory service hide failures? Possibly if the mock doesn't properly simulate the product metadata structure\n- **LLM-Dep**: No LLM involved\n- **Verdict**: This is a filtering logic test. You could test it at Unit (mock the inventory check) or Integration (use a test database with real product records). The real failure would be caught at Unit if the filter logic is wrong, but Integration would better catch issues where the filter isn't being applied to the right collection or where there's an issue with how the product data flows through the system.\n- **Minimum Level**: Integration - we need to ensure the filter is applied across the full recommendation flow with real product records\n\n\n- **Probabilities**: Unit 0.2 (could catch basic logic), Integration 0.7 (catches integration with product data), System 0.1\n\n### Behavior 2: User preference filters work correctly\n- **Description**: Categories in user's blocklist are excluded from results\n- **Mock-Miss**: A mock user preferences service could miss the integration issue\n- **Real-Infra**: Depends on reading user settings from storage\n- **Verdict**: Similar to filtering logic that needs to work across the system. Integration test with real user settings in test DB.\n- **Minimum Level**: Integration - needs to work with actual user preference data\n- **Probabilities**: Unit 0.15, Integration 0.75, System 0.1\n\n### Behavior 3: Recent browsing patterns rank higher\n- **Description**: Products matching recent browsing get higher rank\n- **Mock-Miss**: Mocking browse history could hide scoring issues\n- **Real-Infra**: No real infra needed if we're just testing the ranking algorithm\n- **Verdict**: Testing the ranking algorithm itself. Unit works if we mock input data, but Integration is safer to confirm the ranking algorithm is properly wired into the recommendation flow and actually uses browsing history.\n- **Minimum Level**: Integration - verify the ranking algorithm is correctly integrated with the recommendation flow and uses browsing history properly\n- **Probabilities**: Unit 0.25, Integration 0.65, System 0.1\n\n### Behavior 4: Pagination is stable\n- **Description**: Page 2 returns same results if data doesn't change\n- **Mock-Miss**: Hard to mock pagination bugs - offset/limit logic errors might not show up with small test datasets\n- **Real-Infra**: Pagination bugs often depend on how the data is sorted/retrieved from storage\n- **Verdict**: Need Integration or System level. The real failure would be if the sort order changes between calls due to how the DB orders results, or if there's non-deterministic ordering. Integration with a real database would catch this.\n- **Minimum Level**: Integration - needs consistent ordering, which depends on how results are fetched/sorted\n- **Probabilities**: Unit 0.1, Integration 0.8, System 0.1\n\n### Behavior 5: Serendipity - at least one unbrowsed category\n- **Description**: Recommends from categories user hasn't browsed before\n- **Mock-Miss**: Easy to test with mocks\n- **Real-Infra**: No real infra strictly needed\n- **Verdict**: Testing the serendipity logic itself. Unit with mocks is feasible, but Integration is safer to ensure it works with actual user history data.\n- **Minimum Level**: Integration - verify serendipity logic works with real user history\n- **Probabilities**: Unit 0.2, Integration 0.7, System 0.1\n\n### Behavior 6: New user gets popularity-based recommendations\n- **Description**: Users with no history get popular products\n- **Mock-Miss**: Mocking popularity rankings could hide issues\n- **Real-Infra**: No real infra needed if popularity is pre-computed\n- **Verdict**: Integration level - needs to work with the fallback path and real popularity data\n- **Minimum Level**: Integration\n- **Probabilities**: Unit 0.2, Integration 0.75, System 0.05\n\n### Behavior 7: Click tracking records correct data\n- **Description**: Product ID, position, timestamp are recorded correctly\n- **Mock-Miss**: A mock of the tracking service would be easy to test against\n- **Real-Infra**: Needs to write to storage (could be in-memory DB for testing)\n- **Verdict**: Integration level - the tracking service needs to actually persist data to verify correctness. Mocking the storage layer would miss issues with how data is written or formatted.\n- **Minimum Level**: Integration\n- **Probabilities**: Unit 0.15, Integration 0.8, System 0.05\n\n### Behavior 8: Response time under 200ms for 100k products\n- **Description**: Recommendation generation is fast enough\n- **Mock-Miss**: Mocks would hide real performance issues\n- **Real-Infra**: Real performance depends on actual data volume, sorting, filtering operations\n- **Verdict**: System level - you need a real or realistic-scale test with actual computation to measure performance\n- **Minimum Level**: System - performance testing requires realistic data scale and no mocks that hide algorithmic complexity\n- **Probabilities**: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.1, System 0.85\n\n### Behavior 9: Purchased products are deprioritized\n- **Description**: Algorithm ranks purchased products lower in subsequent recommendations\n- **Mock-Miss**: Mocking purchase history could hide issues\n- **Real-Infra**: No real infra strictly needed\n- **Verdict**: Integration - should verify the algorithm deprioritizes with realistic purchase history\n- **Minimum Level**: Integration\n- **Probabilities**: Unit 0.2, Integration 0.7, System 0.1\n\n### Behavior 10: Deterministic results\n- **Description**: Same user state produces same ranked list on repeated calls\n- **Mock-Miss**: Determinism bugs might not show up with small test sets\n- **Real-Infra**: Could be in-memory, but need to verify the algorithm doesn't use non-deterministic operations\n- **Verdict**: Integration or System? The failure would be if there's randomness in the algorithm or floating-point precision issues with sorting. Could be caught at Integration level if we verify the ranking logic doesn't introduce variability across multiple invocations with identical inputs.\n- **Minimum Level**: Integration\n- **Probabilities**: Unit 0.1, Integration 0.65, System 0.25\n\nI should reconsider the test levels more carefully. Real infrastructure matters when the behavior depends on actual OS-level operations, real network calls, actual filesystem behavior, or real subprocess spawning. System tests are needed when mocks can't replicate what actually happens. For performance testing with large datasets, if it requires a real database handling 100k records or actual HTTP latency, that pushes toward System. But for determinism, Integration testing with repeated calls should surface randomness or precision issues in the ranking algorithm itself. Performance testing at Integration level works with local in-memory structures, whereas System level requires actual infrastructure like real database servers, network latency, or filesystem performance.\n\nMost of these behaviors need Integration as a minimum because they require multiple components interacting together and realistic test data flowing through the system. System level becomes necessary only when you depend on real network calls, actual database servers rather than test databases, real subprocess behavior, OS signals, or genuine API latency.\n\nFor the specific behaviors: out-of-stock filtering and user preference filtering both need Integration to combine product/user data with their respective logic. Browsing pattern ranking requires real history data alongside the ranking algorithm. Pagination stability depends on consistent data persistence and retrieval across modules. The serendipity requirement needs actual user history integrated with the algorithm.\n\nNew user popularity needs the fallback mechanism plus real popularity metrics. Click tracking requires persistent storage across the system. Purchased product deprioritization combines purchase history with the algorithm. Deterministic results verification needs to confirm no random operations are present throughout.\n\nFor response time under 200ms with 100k products, Integration level catches algorithmic inefficiencies (like O(n²) sorting) using a large test dataset, but real database query performance and network latency would only surface at System level. The minimum viable test depends on whether the bottleneck is algorithmic or infrastructure-based. The core issue is whether a test database can adequately simulate production performance characteristics. Integration testing with a properly scaled dataset might catch algorithmic inefficiencies, but real database behavior, network latency, and disk I/O patterns would only surface under System-level testing. Since production failures could stem from these infrastructure-specific factors that a test environment wouldn't replicate, System is the appropriate minimum level.\n\nHowever, reconsidering the actual failure mode: performance degradation typically stems from algorithm or data structure choices rather than infrastructure dependencies. With 100k records in a realistic database structure, Integration testing should expose these issues. The REAL-INFRA criterion asks whether the behavior depends on OS, real network, or subprocess specifics—and response time testing primarily depends on algorithmic efficiency, which Integration can validate. I'll set Integration as the minimum for this behavior.\n\nFor #4, pagination failures could stem from non-deterministic sort ordering or unstable data retrieval between requests—both detectable at Integration level. For #10, non-deterministic recommendation results might arise from unseeded randomness or floating-point precision issues, also catchable at Integration, though concurrency-related data races could push toward System testing.\n\nAcross all ten requirements, Integration testing covers the core scenarios: filter logic against real data, ranking algorithms with actual user history, persistent storage operations, and deterministic behavior without random operations. Response time constraints might benefit from System-level testing given realistic dataset sizes, but Integration remains the baseline for validating each requirement's core functionality.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13457,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13457},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"389247df-2de2-4f43-a052-d042c437a8f3","uuid":"6b90c569-bdee-4740-8254-1a28a34dcf01"}
